(936, 'ERNE - (Energetic and Relativistic Nuclei and Electron Experiment )', 'Particle detector telescopes', NULL, NULL, 1.3, 540, 'MeV', 'Protons, electrons, ions, particle flux', '', '', 'http://www.srl.utu.fi/projects/erne/index_english.html', 'The energy eruptions in the solar atmosphere can lead to the acceleration of local gas particles to extremely high energies and their injection into the interplanetary space. These fast moving streams of particles are recorded by ERNE. At times, when there is no energetic particle production at the Sun, ERNE is observing the continuous flux of energetic particles from Milky Way (galactic cosmic rays) , and from the boundary of the heliosphere accelerated by the termination shock (anomalous cosmic rays). \r\n\r\nERNE Sensor Unit (ESU) has two energetic particle sensors: The Low Energy Detector (LED) and the High Energy Detector (HED).\r\n'),
(937, 'GOLF - Global Oscillations of Low Frequencies ', '', NULL, NULL, 1e-07, 0.02, 'Hz', '', '', '', 'http://www.ias.u-psud.fr/golf/', 'The GOLF experiment aims to study the internal structure of the sun by measuring the spectrum of global oscillations in the frequency range 10^-7 to 10^-2 Hz. Both p and g mode oscillations will be investigated, with the emphasis on the low order long period waves which penetrate the solar core. '),
(938, 'LASCO - Large Angle and Spectrometric Coronagraph', 'Telescopes, coronagraphs, Fabry-Perot interferometer', NULL, NULL, 0, 0, '', '', '', '', 'http://lasco-www.nrl.navy.mil/', 'See also: http://star.mpae.gwdg.de/\r\n\r\nLASCO is a wide-field white light and spectrometric coronagraph consisting of three optical systems having nested fields of view, that together observe the solar corona from just above the limb at 1.1 Rsun, out to very great elongations (32 Rsun).\r\n\r\nThe three telescopes comprising LASCO are designated the C1, with coverage from 1.1 to 3.0 Rsun, the C2, with coverage deliberately overlapping parts of both C1 and C3, and extending from 2.0 to 6.0 Rsun, and the C3, which spans the outer corona from about 3.7 to 32 Rsun. \r\n\r\nThe inner corona instrument, C1, is a newly developed mirror version of the classic Lyot internally occulted coronagraph, while the C2 and C3 are externally occulted instruments. In addition, the C1 is fitted with an imaging Fabry-Perot interferometer, making possible spatially resolved high-resolution coronal spectroscopy in selected spectral emission and absorption lines, between 1.1 and 3.0 Rsun. High definition CCD cameras in each telescope provide detailed images with exceptional dynamic range.'),
(939, 'MDI - Michelson Doppler Imager', 'Imager, interferometer', NULL, NULL, 0, 0, '', '', '', '', 'http://soi.stanford.edu/', 'The MDI observation program was terminated on 12 April 2011. MDI data will continue to be available from the link above for a while. MDI has been superseded by its offspring, SDO/HMI: http://hmi.stanford.edu/'),
(940, 'SUMER - Solar Ultraviolet Measurements of Emitted Radiation', 'Telescope, spectrometer', NULL, NULL, 390, 1610, 'Angstroms', '', '1 - 2 arcsec', '', 'http://www.mps.mpg.de/en/projekte/soho/sumer/', 'SUMER is a UV telescope and spectrometer,  capable of making reliable measurements of bulk motions in the chromosphere, TR and low corona with an accuracy better than 2 km s-1 (Wilhelm et al. 1997), with a spatial resolution of 1 arcsec (one arcsec at L1 corresponds to 715 km on the Sun) across the slit and 2 arcsec along the slit (Lemaire et al. 1997).'),
(941, 'SWAN - Solar Wind Anisotropies', '', NULL, NULL, 115, 180, 'nm', '', '', '5° x 5°', 'http://swan.projet.latmos.ipsl.fr/', 'SWAN does not point directly the Sun. It looks at the solar wind imprint on the Interstellar neutral H flow. The observation principle is called solar wind (or respectively the IS neutral H) Ly-α method. SWAN has been providing almost constant daily observations of the sky in Ly-α. \r\n\r\nThe instrument is equiped with two identical sensor units pointing the northern and southern ecliptic hemispheres respectively. The sensor is completed by a mechanical periscope system containing two mirrors at 45° incidence. The moving mirror system allows full-sky mapping in Ly-α. \r\n\r\nA hydrogen cell is placed in each sensor''s optical path, which provides quantitative information on the spectral profile of the Ly-α line, with a resolving power of about 3 x10^5. '),
(942, 'UVCS - Ultraviolet Coronagraph Spectrometer', 'Reflecting telescopes, coronagraphs, spectrometers, polarimeter', NULL, NULL, 460, 1360, 'Angstroms', '', '', '', 'http://www.cfa.harvard.edu/uvcs/', 'UVCS is composed of three reflecting telescopes with external and internal occultation and a spectrometer assembly consisting of two toric grating spectrometers and a visible light polarimeter. \r\n\r\nThe primary scientific goals of the UVCS are: to locate and characterize the coronal source regions of the solar wind, to identify and understand the dominant physical processes that accelerate the solar wind, to understand how the coronal plasma is heated in solar wind acceleration regions, and to increase the knowledge of coronal phenomena that control the physical properties of the solar wind as determined by in-situ measurements. To progress toward these goals, the UVCS will perform ultraviolet spectroscopy and visible polarimetry to be combined with plasma diagnostic analysis techniques to provide detailed empirical descriptions of the extended solar corona from the coronal base to a heliocentric height of 12 Rsun. '),
(943, 'VIRGO - Variability of Solar Irradiance and Gravity Oscillations', 'Various', NULL, NULL, 0, 0, '', '', '', '', 'http://www.ias.u-psud.fr/virgo/', 'See also: http://www.pmodwrc.ch/pmod.php?topic=tsi/virgo/proj_space_virgo\r\n\r\nThe VIRGO Experiment has three types of instruments to measure total solar irradiance with the absolute radiometers DIARAD and PMO6V, spectral solar irradiance at 402, 500 and 862 nm with a 3-channel sun photometer (SPM) and spectral radiance at 500 nm with a luminosity oscillation imager (LOI).'),
(957, 'X-ray telescopes', 'X-ray telescope', NULL, NULL, 0.15, 15, 'keV', '', '6 arcsec (FWHM)', '30 arcmin', 'http://sci.esa.int/science-e/www/object/index.cfm?fobjectid=31318&fbodylongid=799', 'The telescopes consist of three barrel-shaped mirror modules, each containing 58 "Wolter-type I" wafer-thin concentric mirrors, 0.3 m to 0.7 m in diameter and 0.6 m in length.\r\n\r\nEach telescope includes, apart from the mirror module, baffles for visible and X-ray stray-light suppression and an electron deflector for diverting soft electrons. Two of the telescopes carry a Reflection Grating Array (RGA).'),
(958, 'EPIC - European Photon Imaging Cameras', 'Imager, spectrometer', NULL, NULL, 0.15, 15, 'keV', '', '6 arcsec (FWHM)', '30 arcmin', 'http://sci.esa.int/science-e/www/object/index.cfm?fobjectid=31281&fbodylongid=774', 'The three EPIC cameras offer the possibility to perform extremely sensitive imaging observations over the telescope''s field of view of 30 arcmin and in the energy range from 0.15 to 15 keV with moderate spectral (E/∆E ~ 20-50) and angular resolution (PSF, about 6 arcsec FWHM).'),
(959, 'RGS - Reflection Grating Spectrometer', '', NULL, NULL, 5, 35, 'Angstroms', '', '', '', 'http://sci.esa.int/science-e/www/object/index.cfm?fobjectid=31281&fbodylongid=797', 'For a complementary analysis of the spectrum, two of the three telescopes have a grating structure on their mirror module that reflects about 40 per cent of the incoming rays to a secondary focus, with its own CCD camera. This Reflection Grating Spectrometer (RGS) "fans out" the various wavelengths, thus indicating, in more detail than EPIC, the exact condition of individual elements, such as oxygen and iron.\r\n\r\nThe two reflection grating arrays (RGA) on XMM-Newton are each composed of 182 grating plates. '),
(960, 'OM - Optical Monitor', 'Optical/UV telescope', NULL, NULL, 170, 650, 'nm', '', '', '17 arcmin square', 'http://sci.esa.int/science-e/www/object/index.cfm?fobjectid=31281&fbodylongid=798', 'The third instrument aboard XMM-Newton is a conventional but very sensitive optical/UV telescope, the Optical Monitor (OM). It can observe simultaneously the same regions as the X-ray telescopes, but at ultraviolet and visible wavelengths, providing complementary data about the X-ray sources. \r\n\r\nThe 2-metre long, 30 cm diameter telescope is as sensitive as a four-metre diameter instrument on the Earth''s surface.'),
(1123, 'HIFI - Heterodyne Instrument for the Far Infrared', 'Heterodyne spectrometer', NULL, NULL, 480, 1910, 'GHz', '', '', '', 'http://www.sron.nl/divisions/lea/hifi/', 'Very high resolution heterodyne spectrometer, providing continuous coverage over the range 480 to 1250 GHz in five bands, and 1410 to 1910 GHz in two additional bands. '),
(1124, 'PACS - Photodetector Array Camera and Spectrometer', 'Camera and imaging spectrometer', NULL, NULL, 57, 210, 'µm', 'Operates either as an imaging photometer or an integral field spectrometer over the spectral band.', '', '', 'http://www.mpe.mpg.de/ir/Pacs', ''),
(1125, 'SPIRE - Spectral and Photometric Imaging REciever', 'Camera and imaging spectrometer', NULL, NULL, 200, 700, 'µm', '', '', '', 'http://www.astro.cf.ac.uk/research/instr/projects/?page=spire', 'The SPIRE instrument contains an imaging photometer (camera) and an imaging spectrometer. The camera operates in three wavelength bands centred on 250, 350 and 500 μm, and so can make images of the sky simultaneously in three submillimetre “colours”.  The spectrometer covers the range 200 – 670 μm, allowing the spectral features of atoms and molecules to be measured. '),
(1126, '3.5-m telescope', 'Cassegrain telescope', NULL, NULL, 0, 0, '', '', '', '', 'http://sci.esa.int/science-e/www/object/index.cfm?fobjectid=34690', ''),
(1141, 'MASCS - Mercury Atmospheric and Surface Composition Spectrometer', 'Spectrograph', NULL, NULL, 115, 1450, 'nm', 'Abundance of atmospheric gases around Mercury and detection of minerals in its surface materials', '0.6 nm average spectral res. (UVVS); 5 nm  resolution in 300–1450 nm wavelength range (VIRS)', ' ', 'http://messenger.jhuapl.edu/instruments/MASCS.html', 'MASCS consists of a small Cassegrain telescope with 257-mm effective focal length and a 50-mm aperture that simultaneously feeds an UltraViolet and Visible Spectrometer (UVVS) and a Visible and InfraRed Spectrograph (VIRS).\r\n\r\n\r\nRef: http://www.springerlink.com/content/y5j4w7qm1g315607/'),
(1142, 'EPPS - Energetic Particle and Plasma Spectrometer', 'Spectrometers', NULL, NULL, 0, 0, '', 'Composition, distribution, and energy of charged particles (electrons and various ions) in Mercury''s magnetosphere', '', '160° x 12° for measuring the energy spectra and pitch-angle distribution of ions and electrons', 'http://messenger.jhuapl.edu/instruments/EPPS.html', 'EPPS will measure the mix and characteristics of charged particles in and around Mercury’s magnetosphere using an Energetic Particle Spectrometer (EPS) and a Fast Imaging Plasma Spectrometer (FIPS). Both are equipped with time-of-flight and energy-measurement technologies to determine simultaneously particle velocities and elemental species.\r\n\r\nEPS measures the energy, angular, and compositional distributions of the high-energy components of the in situ electrons (>20 keV) and ions (<5 keV/nucleon), while FIPS measures the energy, angular, and compositional distributions of the low-energy components of the ion distributions (>50 eV/charge to 20 keV/charge).\r\n\r\nRef: http://www.springerlink.com/content/hh71629212632685/'),
(1143, 'MLA - Mercury Laser Alitmeter', 'Altimeter', NULL, NULL, 0, 0, '', '', '1 m from a line-of-sight distance of 1200 km', '', 'http://messenger.jhuapl.edu/instruments/MLA.html', 'MLA maps Mercury’s landforms and other surface characteristics using an infrared laser transmitter and a receiver that measures the round-trip time of individual laser pulses. The data will also be used to track the planet’s slight, forced libration – a wobble about its spin axis – which will tell researchers about the state of Mercury’s core.\r\n\r\nMLA will sample the planet’s surface to within a 1-m range error when the line-of-sight range to Mercury is less than 1,200 km under spacecraft nadir pointing or the slant range is less than 800 km. The altimeter measurements will be used to determine the planet’s forced physical librations by tracking the motion of large-scale topographic features as a function of time. MLA’s laser pulse energy monitor and the echo pulse energy estimate will provide an active measurement of the surface reflectivity at 1,064 nm.\r\n\r\nRef: http://www.springerlink.com/content/c13u866587156310/'),
(1144, 'MAG - Magnetometer', 'Magnetometer', NULL, NULL, 0, 0, '', 'Mercury''s intrinsic magnetic field', '1.6nT (coarse) and 0.047nT (fine)', '  ', 'http://messenger.jhuapl.edu/instruments/MAG.html', 'The Magnetometer (MAG) on the MESSENGER mission is a low-noise, tri-axial, fluxgate instrument with its sensor mounted on a 3.6-m-long boom. \r\n\r\nMAG has a coarse range, ±51,300 nT full scale (1.6-nT resolution), for pre-flight testing, and a fine range, ±1,530 nT full scale (0.047-nT resolution), for Mercury operation.\r\n\r\nRef: http://www.springerlink.com/content/wr8626mvux661g15/'),
(1145, 'XRS - X-Ray Spectrometer', 'Spectrometer', NULL, NULL, 1, 10, 'keV', 'Mg, Al, Si, Na, Ti, Fe', 'Spatial, 42km - 3200km', '12°  x  12°', 'http://messenger.jhuapl.edu/instruments/XRS.html', 'Ref: http://www.springerlink.com/content/w2112557570284r4/ \r\n\r\nMaps mineral composition within the top millimeter of the surface on Mercury by detecting X-ray spectral lines from magnesium, aluminum, sulphur, calcium, titanium, and iron, in the 1-10 keV range.'),
(1146, 'GRNS - Gamma Ray and Neutron Spectrometer', 'Spectrometer', NULL, NULL, 0.1, 10, 'MeV', 'H, O, Na', '&#8776;3.5 keV at FWHM, >5000 events per second, For the spectrometer Energy resolution &#8776;50% for Li-glass and &#8776;30% for the borated plastic scintillator >10,000 events per second', 'For Neutrons, 10cm  x  10cm ', 'http://messenger.jhuapl.edu/instruments/GRNS.html', ''),
(1147, 'MDIS - Mercury Dual Imaging System', 'Imager', NULL, NULL, 350, 1, 'nm', 'Visible and near Infrared light (up to 1100nm),,', '1024 x 1024 pixel array, 14&#956;m pixels', 'Narrow 1.5?, Wide 10.5?  x  ', 'http://messenger.jhuapl.edu/instruments/MDIS.html', 'Ref: http://www.springerlink.com/content/npu6x6v850682p3n/'),
(1199, 'MASCS - Mercury Atmospheric and Surface Composition Spectrometer', 'Spectrograph', NULL, NULL, 115, 1450, 'nm', 'Abundance of atmospheric gases around Mercury and detection of minerals in its surface materials', '0.6 nm average spectral res. (UVVS); 5 nm  resolution in 300–1450 nm wavelength range (VIRS)', ' ', 'http://messenger.jhuapl.edu/instruments/MASCS.html', 'MASCS consists of a small Cassegrain telescope with 257-mm effective focal length and a 50-mm aperture that simultaneously feeds an UltraViolet and Visible Spectrometer (UVVS) and a Visible and InfraRed Spectrograph (VIRS).\r\n\r\n\r\nRef: http://www.springerlink.com/content/y5j4w7qm1g315607/'),
(1200, 'EPPS - Energetic Particle and Plasma Spectrometer', 'Spectrometers', NULL, NULL, 0, 0, '', 'Composition, distribution, and energy of charged particles (electrons and various ions) in Mercury''s magnetosphere', '', '160° x 12° for measuring the energy spectra and pitch-angle distribution of ions and electrons', 'http://messenger.jhuapl.edu/instruments/EPPS.html', 'EPPS will measure the mix and characteristics of charged particles in and around Mercury’s magnetosphere using an Energetic Particle Spectrometer (EPS) and a Fast Imaging Plasma Spectrometer (FIPS). Both are equipped with time-of-flight and energy-measurement technologies to determine simultaneously particle velocities and elemental species.\r\n\r\nEPS measures the energy, angular, and compositional distributions of the high-energy components of the in situ electrons (>20 keV) and ions (<5 keV/nucleon), while FIPS measures the energy, angular, and compositional distributions of the low-energy components of the ion distributions (>50 eV/charge to 20 keV/charge).\r\n\r\nRef: http://www.springerlink.com/content/hh71629212632685/'),
(1201, 'MLA - Mercury Laser Alitmeter', 'Altimeter', NULL, NULL, 0, 0, '', '', '1 m from a line-of-sight distance of 1200 km', '', 'http://messenger.jhuapl.edu/instruments/MLA.html', 'MLA maps Mercury’s landforms and other surface characteristics using an infrared laser transmitter and a receiver that measures the round-trip time of individual laser pulses. The data will also be used to track the planet’s slight, forced libration – a wobble about its spin axis – which will tell researchers about the state of Mercury’s core.\r\n\r\nMLA will sample the planet’s surface to within a 1-m range error when the line-of-sight range to Mercury is less than 1,200 km under spacecraft nadir pointing or the slant range is less than 800 km. The altimeter measurements will be used to determine the planet’s forced physical librations by tracking the motion of large-scale topographic features as a function of time. MLA’s laser pulse energy monitor and the echo pulse energy estimate will provide an active measurement of the surface reflectivity at 1,064 nm.\r\n\r\nRef: http://www.springerlink.com/content/c13u866587156310/'),
(1202, 'MAG - Magnetometer', 'Magnetometer', NULL, NULL, 0, 0, '', 'Mercury''s intrinsic magnetic field', '1.6nT (coarse) and 0.047nT (fine)', '  ', 'http://messenger.jhuapl.edu/instruments/MAG.html', 'The Magnetometer (MAG) on the MESSENGER mission is a low-noise, tri-axial, fluxgate instrument with its sensor mounted on a 3.6-m-long boom. \r\n\r\nMAG has a coarse range, ±51,300 nT full scale (1.6-nT resolution), for pre-flight testing, and a fine range, ±1,530 nT full scale (0.047-nT resolution), for Mercury operation.\r\n\r\nRef: http://www.springerlink.com/content/wr8626mvux661g15/'),
(1203, 'XRS - X-Ray Spectrometer', 'Spectrometer', NULL, NULL, 1, 10, 'keV', 'Mg, Al, Si, Na, Ti, Fe', 'Spatial, 42km - 3200km', '12°  x  12°', 'http://messenger.jhuapl.edu/instruments/XRS.html', 'Ref: http://www.springerlink.com/content/w2112557570284r4/ \r\n\r\nMaps mineral composition within the top millimeter of the surface on Mercury by detecting X-ray spectral lines from magnesium, aluminum, sulphur, calcium, titanium, and iron, in the 1-10 keV range.'),
(1204, 'GRNS - Gamma Ray and Neutron Spectrometer', 'Spectrometer', NULL, NULL, 0, 0, '', 'H, O, Na, Mg, Si, Ca, Ti, Fe, K, Th', '', '', 'http://messenger.jhuapl.edu/instruments/GRNS.html', 'Ref: http://www.springerlink.com/content/k732215880714128/ \r\n\r\nThe GRNS consists of separate gamma-ray and neutron spectrometers to collect complementary data on elements that form Mercury''s crust: The Gamma-Ray Spectrometer (GRS) measures gamma rays emitted by the nuclei of atoms on Mercury’s surface that are struck by cosmic rays; and the Neutron Spectrometer (NS) maps variations in the fast, thermal, and epithermal neutrons Mercury’s surface emits when struck by cosmic rays.\r\n\r\nThe GRS portion detects gamma-ray emissions in the 0.1- to 10-MeV energy range and achieves an energy resolution of 3.5 keV full-width at half-maximum for 60Co (1332 keV).\r\n\r\nThe NS sensor consists of a sandwich of three scintillation detectors working in concert to measure the flux of ejected neutrons in three energy ranges from thermal to ~7 MeV. '),
(1205, 'MDIS - Mercury Dual Imaging System', 'Imager', NULL, NULL, 395, 1040, 'nm (Wide)', 'Visible and near Infrared light (up to 1100nm)', '20–50 meters/pixel (Narrow), 250 metres/pixel (Wide)', '1.5° x 1.5° (Narrow), 10.5° x 10.5° (Wide)  ', 'http://messenger.jhuapl.edu/instruments/MDIS.html', 'Ref: http://www.springerlink.com/content/npu6x6v850682p3n/ \r\n\r\nMDIS consists of a monochrome narrow-angle camera (NAC) and a multispectral wide-angle camera (WAC). The NAC is a 1.5° field-of-view (FOV) off-axis reflector, coaligned with the WAC, a four-element refractor with a 10.5° FOV and 12-colour filter wheel. The focal plane electronics of each camera are identical and use a 1024×1024 Atmel (Thomson) TH7888A CCD detector.'),
(1206, 'RS - Radio Science', 'Various', NULL, NULL, 0, 0, '', '', '', '', 'http://messenger.jhuapl.edu/instruments/RS.html', 'Measures the gravity of Mercury and the state of the planetary core by utilizing the spacecraft positioning data.'),
(1207, 'CRIS - Cosmic Ray Isotope Spectrometer', 'Spectrometer', NULL, NULL, 250, 250, 'cm²-sr', 'Species: 2 ≤ Z ≤ 30; Quantities: Z, M, E', 'mass resolution, 0.25 amu ', '', '', 'Typical Energy (MeV/nuc): ~ 200\r\nTechnique: dE/dx - E'),
