(56, 'Contact information, including Gemini staff and details of the partnership offices can be found at http://www.gemini.edu/contact', 'Future instruments:\r\n\r\nGPI - The Gemini Planetary Imager is currently under development. Assuming the current schedule, the instrument will be delivered to Gemini South in middle 2012. GPI will be used to carry out large Campaign programmes as well as standard science programmes via the TAC system. It is expected that the earliest science observing will be in semester 2013A pending results from Acceptance Testing and Commissioning. GPI is an extreme adaptive-optics imaging polarimeter/integral-field spectrometer, which will provide diffraction-limited data between 0.9 and 2.4  microns. \r\n\r\nFLAMINGOS-2 is a Near-Infrared wide field imager and multi-object spectrometer. The formal science commissioning of this instrument started in December 2011 and is expected to last until the middle of 2012.\r\n\r\nGSAOI - The Gemini South Adaptive Optics Imager is a near-infrared adaptive optics camera that will be used with the Gemini Multi-conjugate Adaptive Optics System (GeMS). GSAOI will be commissioned along with GeMS, during most 2011 and 2012.\r\n\r\nFurther information about all Gemini South instruments can be found here:\r\nhttp://www.gemini.edu/sciops/instruments/?q=sciops/instruments', '', 'GCAL - Gemini Facility Calibration Unit is available on each Gemini telescope, providing continuum and line emission light sources for wavelength and flat-field calibrations.\r\n\r\nGeMs is the Gemini Multi-Conjugated Adaptive Optics System. This facility instrument delivers a uniform, diffraction limited image quality at near-infrared (NIR) wavelengths over an extended FoV of more than 1 arcmin across. This corrected beam then feeds the new generation of science instruments: Flamingos-2 or GSAOI. ', '', '', 'Gemini was built and is operated by a partnership of 7 countries with a national office for each partner. These are: The United States Gemini Office, The United Kingdom Gemini Office, The Canadian Gemini Office, The Australian Gemini Office, The Argentinian Gemini Office, The Brazilian Gemini Office, The Chilean Gemini Office, University of Hawaii Gemini Office. The partnership is managed by the Association of Universities for Research in Astronomy (AURA). ', ''),
(57, 'Contact information, including Gemini staff and details of the partnership offices can be found at http://www.gemini.edu/contact', 'TEXES - the Texas Echelon Cross Echelle Spectrograph - is a high resolution (~100,000) mid-infrared (5-25 micron) spectrometer, which was offered at Gemini North as a visitor instrument in previous years and may be available in the future. \r\n\r\nSee further details about this instrument and future availability here:\r\nhttp://www.gemini.edu/sciops/instruments/texes/?q=sciops/instruments/texes', '', 'ALTAIR - ALTtitude conjugate Adaptive optics for the InfraRed - is the facility natural/laser guide star adaptive optics system of the Gemini North telescope. It can feed a corrected beam to Gemini instruments NIRI and NIFS. \r\n\r\nGCAL - Gemini Facility Calibration Unit is available on each Gemini telescope, providing continuum and line emission light sources for wavelength and flat-field calibrations.', '', '', 'Gemini was built and is operated by a partnership of 7 countries with a national office for each partner. These are: The United States Gemini Office, The United Kingdom Gemini Office, The Canadian Gemini Office, The Australian Gemini Office, The Argentinian Gemini Office, The Brazilian Gemini Office, The Chilean Gemini Office, University of Hawaii Gemini Office. The partnership is managed by the Association of Universities for Research in Astronomy (AURA). ', ''),
