(1629, 'The 32-m Antenna', 10, 0, 18, 32.000000, '', 11, 'radiowaves, ', 1.400000, 1, 22.000000, 5, 'The 32 m parabolic antenna is used for both single dish observations and interferometry. In interferometry it works together with the other EVN antennas, installed all over Europe, in order to produce very high resolution images, which are useful for detailed radio sources studies. In single dish, it is mainly used for: H2O and methanol maser spectrometry, monitoring of extragalactic compact sources flux variability, galactic polarimetric surveys, studies of comets, extrasolar planet research, and radar monitoring of Near Earth Objects (in collaboration with the NASA)  '),
(1630, 'The Northern Cross', 10, 0, 65, 0.000000, '', 1, 'radiowave, ', 408.000000, 1, 0.000000, 1, 'The Northern Cross is, currently, composed of two perpendicular arms that are 564 m long (East-West) and 640 m long (North-South) and it has a useable total surface area of 30000 m^2. Thanks to this vast area the antenna is capable of detecting very weak radio sources.\r\n\r\nIt has been mainly used to effect high sensitivity sky surveys and, thus, to produce large radio-source catalogues.\r\nIt has been used for pulsars research and for the spectrometric study of interstellar dust (emission line of ionized hydrogen and of ionized carbon). \r\n\r\nThe E-W arm is constituted by a single antenna having a parabolic-cylinder shape, for a length of 564 m and a width of 35 m. 1536 dipoles are aligned along the focal axis, which is parallel to the rotation axis - 20 m distant from it. Every dipole is distant 36 cm from the following one, and its task is to turn the incoming radio wave into a measurable electric signal.\r\n\r\nThe N-S arm is made up of 64 parallel antennas (parabolic cylinders), having a length of 23.5 m and a width of 8 m. The distance between two consecutive antennas is 10 m. Similarly to what happens on the E-W arm, 64 dipoles are located on the focal axis of every antenna.'),
